  "footnotes": [
    "Magadha (c.600–322 BCE): The dominant Mahajanapada of the Gangetic plain. The Haryanka, Shishunaga, and Nanda dynasties ruled from Rajagriha and Pataliputra. Magadha was the birthplace of both Buddhism (Bodh Gaya) and Jainism (Vaishali), and the base from which the Maurya and Gupta empires unified India.",
    "Maurya Empire (322–185 BCE): Chandragupta Maurya, guided by Kautilya (Chanakya), overthrew the Nanda dynasty. Ashoka's conquest of Kalinga (c.261 BCE) and subsequent conversion to Buddhism led to the first pan-Indian state and one of the earliest examples of state-sponsored religious tolerance.",
    "Gupta Empire (c.320–550 CE): The 'Golden Age of India'. Achievements include the decimal numeral system, Aryabhata's astronomy, Kalidasa's poetry, Ajanta cave paintings, and the formalization of Sanskrit grammar. The Gupta collapse under Hunnic invasions fragmented North India for centuries.",
    "Tripartite Struggle (c.750–1000 CE): The Gurjara-Pratiharas, Rashtrakutas, and Palas fought for control of Kannauj — the symbolic imperial capital of North India. This three-way conflict defined the political geography of early medieval India.",
    "Chola Empire (c.985–1070): Under Rajaraja I and Rajendra I, the Cholas built a maritime empire that spanned Sri Lanka, the Maldives, and reached the Srivijaya kingdom in Southeast Asia. Rajendra I's naval expedition to the Ganges earned him the title 'Gangaikondachola'. The Brihadeeswarar Temple at Thanjavur remains their greatest architectural legacy.",
    "Delhi Sultanate (1206–1526): Five successive dynasties (Mamluk, Khalji, Tughluq, Sayyid, Lodi) ruled from Delhi. Alauddin Khalji repelled multiple Mongol invasions. The Sultanate introduced Persian court culture, Islamic architecture (Qutb Minar), and the iqta revenue system to South Asia.",
    "Mughal Empire (1526–1857): Founded by Babur. Akbar's religious tolerance (Din-i-Ilahi, sulh-i-kul), Shah Jahan's Taj Mahal, and Aurangzeb's maximalist expansion defined the empire. At its peak (c.1700), it governed 150 million people — roughly one-quarter of the world's population — and produced nearly a quarter of global GDP.",
    "Partition of India (1947): The largest mass migration in human history. 10–20 million displaced; 200,000–2,000,000 killed in communal violence. Pakistan (West & East) created as a Muslim homeland. East Pakistan became Bangladesh after the 1971 Liberation War."
  ]
